 Herder, and Hegel, in this development. Beginning with the first English translation of Walter Demel’s classic essay “How the Chinese Became Yellow,” the collection’s essays examine the connections between eighteenth-century philosophy, German Orientalism, and the origins of modern race theory.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Aug 2021) 0aChinese in literature. 0aEnlightenmentxGermany. 0aEnlightenmentzGermany. 0aGerman literaturexHistory and criticismx18th century. 0aGerman literaturexHistory and criticismy18th century. 0aGerman literaturey18th centuryxHistory and criticism. 0aOrientalism in literature. 0aOrientalismxHistoryx18th centuryxGermany. 0aOrientalismzGermanyxHistoryy18th century. 0aPhilosophy, Germanx18th century. 0aPhilosophy, Germany18th century. 0aRace in literature. 7aHISTORY / Europe / General.2bisacsh1 aBernasconi, Robert, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBrandt, Bettina, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBrandt, Bettina, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aCarhart, Michael C., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDemel, Walter, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLibrett, Jeffrey S., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aNiekerk, Carl, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aNoyes, John K., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPerkins, Franklin, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPurdy, Daniel , eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aPurdy, Daniel Leonhard, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aTautz, Birgit, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.g